  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 13-19.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "The refusal of the Pharisees to accept this claim on his unsupported testimony, and Christ's reply.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 13.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The fact that the Pharisees respond shows that the circumstances of the previous day are changed. They have been the secret and organized opponents of Jesus throughout. The synoptic Gospels show with what perverse ingenuity and doggedness they followed him from place to place, venturing to assail him through his disciples, through his omissions of ritual, and by reason of his Divine freedom in interpreting the sacred Scripture; nor did they refrain from attributing his miracles to the power of the evil one (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). They were the nucleus of the bitter opposition to him current among the rulers in Jerusalem, and they reveal here a reminiscence of the discussion which had taken place in the temple or its neighbourhood after the healing of the impotent man (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). There the Lord had said that if he bore witness of himself, without any corroboration, his witness, thus isolated and deprived of evidence, would, on the ordinary grounds of a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "prima facie",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " testimony, not be true; but be went on to say, further, that his testimony was variously corroborated by the manifest presence and cooperation of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the Father.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Forgetting thus his own vindication of himself - which many months of varied proof of his personality had confirmed for candid minds - they assail his comparison of himself to the Light of the world, with: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thou",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "bearest witness of thyself; thy witness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - according to the canon he had himself admitted and supplemented; but they forgetting the supplement, add - (thy witness) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "is not true.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"If thou art simply making such exalted claims as this, in forgetfulness of the well known maxim about self-witness, we take the liberty to dispute and reject it.\" John 8:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Thou barest record of thyself",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Rev., witness. A technical objection, evading the real purport of Jesus' declaration. The Rabbinical writings declared that no man could give witness for himself. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
